This shows that each author tends to have certain writing style based on the frequency of words his uses. Although there seem to be some overlaps between Hamilton and Madison, in general we see some clear patterns based on the clusters. We didn’t scale the data because word frequency is comparable among documents so we didn’t need to scale for comparability.

Experiment2: PCA with scaling + LDA

# First, need to remove columns for the tokens that vary (probably don't appear in y)
absent <- which(apply(y, 2, var)==0)
z <- y[, -absent]

# we then do LDA
library(MASS)

#choose 40 pincipal components to start with 
w <- as.matrix(y) %*% p$rotation[, 1:40] 
l <- lda(w, grouping=b)

#make a null lineup to compare observed separation of the documents with null results
par(mfrow = c(3, 3))
answer <- sample(1:9, 1)
for (i in 1:9) {
  if (i == answer) {
    # LDA for the original data
    plot(as.matrix(w) %*% l$scaling[, 1:2], col=b)
  } else {
    # LDA with labels reassigned at random
    B <- sample(b, length(b))
    L <- lda(w, grouping=B)
    plot(as.matrix(w) %*% L$scaling[, 1:2], col=B)
  }
}

From the 9 plots we can clearly see that there is a true plot, which shows clear clusters of points.

#look at the true plot 
plot(as.matrix(w) %*% l$scaling[, 1:2], col=b)
legend("topright", levels(b), text.col=1:length(b),
       fill=1:length(levels(b)))

From the plot we can see that after performing PCA then LDA, the patterns are more clear. There seem to be separate clusters of documents written by different authors.

We can see that as we reduce the number of principal components, the points become less clustered. Fewer number of PCs means that we are capturing less variance of the data. This allows the points to have more freedom to be spread out. As a result, we see that the clusters of points are not so centralized compared to when we use 40 PCs.

Part VI: Perform 100 cross-validation trials with y, each time training your classi cation procedure (presumably PCA then LDA) on 66 of the points, then seeing how well the classification performs on 5 test points.

Approach 1: Use PCA then LDA to find the classification error rate on 5 test points

set.seed(2048)
#create lists to store confusion matrix and classification errors for the trainning and testing datasets 
train.tables <- vector(mode = "list", length = 100)
train.errorlist <- vector(mode = "list", length = 100)

test.tables <- vector(mode = "list", length = 100)
test.errorlist <- vector(mode = "list", length = 100)

#perform 100 cross validations
for (i in 1:100){
  
  leave <- sample(1:nrow(y), 5)
  train <- y[-leave, ]
  b.train <- b[-leave]
  p <- prcomp(train)
  l <- lda(as.matrix(train) %*% p$rotation[, 1:40], grouping=b.train)
  
  # train prediction 
  pred.train <- predict(l, as.matrix(y[-leave, ]) %*%  p$rotation[,1:40])$class
  tbl.train<- table(pred.train, b[-leave])
  
  # test prediction 
  pred.test <- predict(l, as.matrix(y[leave, ]) %*% p$rotation[, 1:40])$class
  tbl.test<- table(pred.test, b[leave])
  
  # training error rate 
  error.train<-1-(sum(diag(tbl.train)/sum(tbl.train)))
  train.tables[[i]] <- tbl.train
  train.errorlist[i]<-error.train
  
  # testing error rate
  error.test<-1-(sum(diag(tbl.test)/sum(tbl.test)))
  test.tables[[i]] <- tbl.test
  test.errorlist[i]<-error.test
}

Approach 2: We want to further explore the model’s classification performance by doing 10-fold cross validation and identify the best number of principal components to use for the PCA + LDA

set.seed(2018)
#write a function to find the best number principal components 
find.PC<-function(x, y, Kfold, pc_list)
  {
  
  n <- length(y)

  shuffle_idx=sample(seq(n),replace = F,size = n)
  x.shuffled=x[shuffle_idx,]
  y.shuffled=y[shuffle_idx]

  error_list=rep(0,length(pc_list))

  for (i in 1:length(pc_list)){

    pc=pc_list[i]
    for (k in 1:Kfold){
      idx.val <- seq((k - 1)*n/Kfold + 1, k*n/Kfold, 1)
      x.val <- x.shuffled[idx.val,]  #set validation data
      y.val <- y.shuffled[idx.val]
      x.train <- x.shuffled[-idx.val,]  #set training data
      y.train <- y.shuffled[-idx.val]

      #train
      p <- prcomp(x.train)
      l <- lda(as.matrix(x.train) %*% p$rotation[, 1:pc], grouping=y.train)

      #predict
      y.pred=predict(l, as.matrix(x.val) %*% p$rotation[, 1:pc])$class

      #update prediction error
      error_list[i] <- error_list[i] + mean(y.pred!=y.val)  
    }
    error_list[i] <- error_list[i] / Kfold
  }
  return(list('best_pc'=pc_list[which.min(error_list)], 'errors'=error_list))
}

# do a 10-fold cross validation 
result=find.PC(y,b,Kfold=10,seq(0,30,1))
best_pc=result$best_pc
best_pc
## [1] 19
plot(seq(0,30,1),result$errors,type='o',col='blue')

From the plot we can see that the error generally decreases as we increase the number of principal components from 0 to 10. Then the error fluctuates. We can guess that the best number of pincipal components is between 10 to 20. In this case, the best number of PC is 19.

In conclusion, our PCA + LDA model works pretty well in predicting the document’s authorship. For the 100 cross validation trials that we did, we get 4 trials with misclassification error 0.2 or 0.4. And we get 96 trials with misclassification error 0. By using the k-fold cross validation, we find that the best number of principal components to use is 18. However, we shouldn’t be too confident about predicting all documents with unknown authorships because they might be harder to classify than the cross-validation test documents that we used. Also, joint authorship is possible, so for some misclassified documents, there might not be an error because the documents could be attributed to multiple authors.
